 Farming-based Money flow 18 (1998) 21-30 
 
 AGRICULTURAL 
 ECONOMICS 
 
 ElSEVIER 
 
 Buyer preferences for sheep and goats in southern Nigeria: A 
 (related to feeling pleasure) price analysis 
 M.A. Jabbar 
 International Animals Research Institute (/LRI), P. 0. Box 5689, Addis Ababa, Ethiopia 
 
 Accepted 30 July 1997 
 
 Abstract 
 A survey of two (away from cities) markets in southwest Nigeria over 14 months showed that supplies, sales and prices of sheep and goats varied 
 widely during the period with a sharp peak during the Muslim special celebration of Eid-e1-Kabir and a smaller peak during the Christmas-New Year 
 period. Local West African Dwarf (WAD) sheep and goats and northern Y' ankasa sheep and Red Sokoto goats were traded in the markets 
 and animals were (bought something for money) for rearing, trading, (formal, special events or series of actions), butchering/ catering, sacrifice, and special celebrations. There were a big differences 
 between species /breeds (bought something for money) for different purposes. A (related to feeling pleasure) price model was fitted to decide/figure out factors influencing price. After 
 changes/recalculations were made for age, weight, sex, time of transaction and market, WAD sheep commanded higher prices than WAD goats and 
 Red Sokoto goats for all purposes except for butchering/ catering; Red Sokoto goats commanded almost the same  or lower prices than WAD goats 
 depending on the purpose for (instance of buying something for money); and Y'ankasa sheep, mostly (bought something for money) for the Eid-el-Kabir special celebration, commanded (only a little bit) 
 higher prices than WAD sheep. The (your share of sales out of all sales) of WAD sheep is now small and is under competition from northern sheep and goats, 
 so increased production of WAD sheep in the south will benefit both producers and people in the area. In general, the results point to/show 
 that buyers have preferences for clearly stated/particular breeds and species for clearly stated/particular purposes, so producers and sellers may benefit by targeting specific 
 buyer categories and times of the year. Published by Elsevier Science B.V. 
 Keywords: Sheep and goat trade; (related to feeling pleasure) price model; Nigeria 
 
 1. Background and goals 
 Trypanotolerant West African Dwarf (WAD) 
 sheep and goats are the most common (buffalo, deer, antelope, etc.) 
 species kept by small-scale crop farmers in the humid zone of west and central Africa. Of the 19.8 
 million small (buffaloes, deer, antelopes, etc.) in the zone, over 60% are 
 WAD goats (Mcintire et al., 1992). Nearly half of 
 the small (buffaloes, deer, antelopes, etc.) of humid zone are found in 
 Nigeria (Jahnke, 1982). As the group demand for 
 small (buffalo, deer, antelope, etc.) meat in the zone goes beyond supply 
 from local sources, the gap is met by supplies from 
 the subhumid and semiarid zones in the north of the 
 country and beyond. In the past, only southern city-based 
 markets used to be served by northern animals but in 
 the last few years, northern animals have started penetrat0169-5150/98/$17.00 Published by Elsevier Science B.V. 
 PII S0169-5150(97)00038-8 
 
 ing southern (away from cities) markets, and the share of northern 
 animals in the southern markets has been increasing. 
 Mostly, Red Sokoto goats and Y'ankasa sheep 
 are exported to the southern markets, and more goats 
 than sheep are exported (Francis, 1990; Jabbar, 1995). 
 Of all the animals traded in the southern (away from cities) 
 markets, only a few are (bought) by local villagers 
 for rearing, some are bought by traders to resell live 
 or as meat and most of the animals are bought by 
 different types of people for (formal, special events or series of actions) and 
 special celebrations, e.g., birth, marriage, funeral, sacrifice, 
 Christmas and Eid-el-Kabir (Sandford, 1982; Francis, 1990; Jabbar, 1995). It is common among Christians, Muslims and believers in spirits in the area to offer to 
 sacrifice an animal if a wish is satisfied, e.g., if a sick 
 person gets well. (usually/ in a common and regular way), the meat of the sacrifi- 
 
 22 
 
 M.A. Jabbar /Agricultural Money flow 18 (1997) 21-30 
 
 cial animal is distributed among poor neighbours. 
 Muslims also sacrifice animals on the occasion of 
 Eid-el-Kabir (also called Eid-el-Adha) special celebration to 
 remember predictor of the future Ibrahim's (predictor of the future Abraham 
 in Christian religion) response to god's wish to 
 sacrifice his son to prove his commitment, love and 
 loyalty to god. Since Muslims follow Moon-related calendar, 
 this occasion moves forward by 10-11 days every 
 year. 
 Earlier market and price surveys in southern 
 Nigeria have generally shown that supplies, sales and 
 prices of small (buffaloes, deer, antelopes, etc.) peak at special celebration times and 
 that the price of a particular species /breed depends 
 on animal attributes such as weight, sex, time of 
 sale, location of market (Okali, 1979; Okali and 
 Upton, 1985; Francis and Ingawa, 1988; Francis, 
 1990; Jabbar, 1995). These studies have also shown 
 that (in name only/very small amount) prices of southern species /breeds were 
 lower than that for northern species /breeds but in 
 the (not being there; not being present) of appropriate changes/recalculations for animal 
 (features/ qualities/ traits) like age, weight and sex, the price 
 comparisons may not reflect true differences. More than that, these studies did not think about/believe the possibility of 
 any significant price differences between animals 
 (bought something for money) for different purposes. Andargachew and 
 Brokken (1993) have found significant price differences between small (buffaloes, deer, antelopes, etc.) (bought something for money) for different purposes in the Ethiopian markets. 
 The goals of this paper are to decide/figure out if 
 buyers of small (buffaloes, deer, antelopes, etc.) in southern Nigeria have 
 planned preferences for clearly stated/particular species /breeds 
 for clearly stated/particular purposes, and whether they pay very different prices for different species /breeds 
 agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with their preferences. Answers to these 
 questions have important effects/results/suggestions for the local 
 and northern producers who supply the southern 
 markets. Any significant price differences by 
 species /breeds, purpose and time of (instance of buying something for money) would 
 mean that producers and sellers could benefit by 
 targetting clearly stated/particular buyer categories and times of the 
 year to sell their animals. 
 
 2. Materials and methods 
 2.1. Source of data 
 Two (away from cities) markets-Oja and Apomu-were 
 watched/supervised in Oyo state, southwest Nigeria. Oja is 
 
 located about 10 km outside Oyo town, and Apomu, 
 about 35 km away from lbadan, a large city. These 
 markets are functionally independent in the sense 
 that their supply country and service areas are 
 mostly different. Both are general valuable thing markets, a section of which is used for trading small 
 (buffaloes, deer, antelopes, etc.). Both the markets (usually/ in a common and regular way) meet every 4 
 days, and more often before major special celebrations 
 such as Christmas and Eid-el-Kabir. Data were collected each market day from the buyers and the 
 sellers of all the animals traded except that during 
 special celebration periods when large number of animals were 
 traded, records of a random sample of animals were 
 taken. Data were collected for the period December 
 1989 to January 1991. During this period, the two 
 markets met for a total of 223 days and records were 
 collected of 4504 traded animals. 
 For each traded animal, data were collected on 
 price, species, breed, sex, age (months), live weight 
 (kg), seller type, seller sex, buyer type, buyer sex, 
 reason for sale, reason for (instance of buying something for money) or meant use 
 of the animal. Animals are not (usually/ in a common and regular way) weighed by 
 buyers and sellers in the market but an ability by 
 either side to make a good guess about weight helps 
 in making a good (deal with a good price/agreement between people). However, for the purposes 
 of this study, each traded animal was weighed on a 
 scale immediately after the buyer and the seller 
 reached an agreement to exchange. Age was measured by examining teeth and by talking to the seller 
 and the buyer. Some general (features/ qualities/ traits) of this 
 sample were reported earlier (Jabbar, 1995) and the 
 results of more difficult/strict/high quality price analysis are presented 
 in this paper. 
 2.2. (related to careful studying or deep thinking) method 
 
 A (related to feeling pleasure) price model was used to decide/figure out the 
 effects of different factors on price. A (related to feeling pleasure) price 
 function relates the price of a product (good or 
 service) to its different attributes or (features/ qualities/ traits). 
 Waugh (1928) and later Lancaster (1971) made early 
 tries to relate price to product (features/ qualities/ traits). 
 Rosen (1974) and Lucas (1975) advanced those ideas 
 providing a possible (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) for (related to feeling pleasure) price 
 analysis. The hidden (under) guess of such analysis 
 is that products have utility bearing attributes and 
 that the values of those attributes add/give to the 
 price of the product. The watched/followed product price is 
 
 M.A. Jabbar /Agricultural Money flow 18 (1997) 21-30 
 
 therefore a (thing made up of different things) of the understood values of the 
 product's attributes. 
 The explanation of (related to feeling pleasure) pricing offers no suggestion about the functional form controlling/ruling the 
 relationship between price and different attributes, 
 this is carefully thought about/believed a matter for scientific desire/decision (Williams, 1989). The possible (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) 
 suggested by Rosen (1974) assumes competitive 
 market structure where people' bid functions and 
 suppliers' offer price functions are always mostly unrelated 
 at the balance. So (related to feeling pleasure) price function is 
 mostly a function of product attributes and not of 
 individual buyer and seller attributes (Oczkowski, 
 1994). This means that only products are (made different), while their markets, buyers and sellers are not. 
 In most scientific studies, however, linear moving backward 
 models have been used with product as well as 
 market and market agent attributes as (numbers that change/things that change) suggesting the existence of elements of noncompetitiveness in the (connected/related) product market being (examined closely) (see for example, Brorsen et al., 1984; Francis, 
 1990; Parker, 1993; Parker and Zilberman, 1993; 
 Andargachew and Brokken, 1993; Williams et al., 
 1993; Oczkowski, 1994; Rodriguez et al., 1995). 
 Most (related to feeling pleasure) moving backward models use a set of 
 (numbers-based) (continuous) (numbers that change/things that change), a set of (not numbers-based) (separate) (numbers that change/things that change) in the form of dummies, and 
 sometimes a set of interaction (numbers that change/things that change). For 
 (numbers-based) (numbers that change/things that change) in the moving backward, the (pertaining to each person or thing) partial almost the same as the function represents the 
 understood not important attribute price. For (not numbers-based) (numbers that change/things that change), the guessed coefficient measures the hit/effect 
 of the presence of the given attribute. In this case, 
 the understood ((described the future)) price cannot be came/coming from 
 a partial derivative but needs/demands added/more moving around/misleading and tricking (Gujarati, 1988). In models with many (not numbers-based) attributes each with a few categories needing/ordering 
 many dummy (numbers that change/things that change) and many interaction 
 terms, the number of terms in the equation may 
 . become large. In such cases, the guess of the 
 (described the future) prices becomes awkward and at times 
 hard to understand/explain and compare (see for example, 
 Francis, 1990; Andargachew and Brokken, 1993; 
 Rodriguez et al., 1995). 
 An other choice is to use Analysis of Covariance 
 (AnCov) way of doing things which is a combination of linear 
 moving backward and analysis of variance (ANOVA). In the 
 AnCov way of doing things, the ANOVA results are (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) 
 
 23 
 
 for the linear relationships between the dependent 
 (number or thing that changes) and the covariates (Norusis, 1993). The 
 general clear form of the AnCov model may be 
 written as: P = F(Q,C) + U, where P is the watched/followed price of a product, Q is a set of factors 
 ((not numbers-based) (numbers that change/things that change)) each with more than one categories, C is a set of covariates ((numbers-based) (numbers that change/things that change)), and U is a leftover/extra error term. (connected/related) 
 interaction terms may be optionally included in the 
 model. The guessed limits/guidelines of the model can 
 be used to guess the (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) mean prices of 
 different categories of a product, e.g., male and 
 female sheep: (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) prices are guessed prices if 
 both male and female were of the same attributes. In 
 a multifactor, multicovariate model, the limits/guidelines 
 for categories of a factor are guessed by (changing to make better/changing to fit new conditions) 
 the effects of all other factors and the covariates. 
 With (happening together) or combined confidence periods of time (or space) created by the model, the importance of differences 
 of the limits/guidelines of different categories of a factor 
 can be compared (Norusis, 1993; Gujarati, 1988). In 
 way of thinking/basic truth/rule, linear moving backward and AnCov ways of doing things 
 perform the same function but (a) little differently. 
 The principal advantage of AnCov results is that 
 they can be understood/explained more directly and easily to 
 compare differences between categories of a factor. 
 In this study, the AnCov way of doing things was employed 
 using the General Factorial Analysis of Variance 
 procedure of SPSS for Windows to guess limits/guidelines (Norusis, 1993). The factors and covariates used 
 are discussed in Section 3.2. 
 
 3. Results 
 3.1. General (features/ qualities/ traits) of the data 
 Of the 4504 animals traded in the two markets, 
 69% were WAD goats, 9% WAD sheep, 21% Red 
 Sokoto goats and 1% were Y' ankasa sheep (Table 
 1). There were a small number of Red Kano goats 
 and Balarni sheep from the north which were (match up each pair of items in order) combined with Red Sokoto goats and Y'ankasa 
 sheep in this analysis. Of all the animals, 76% were 
 sold by farmers from the surrounding areas of the 
 two markets, and 26% by traders. Of all the traded 
 animals, 24% were (bought something for money) by farmers for rearing, 
 27% by traders for resale in the same or other (away from cities) 
 
