 markets or in the city-based  markets, 16% by butchers 
 and catering restaurants, 20% by people for different (formal, special events or series of actions), 10% by people for different 
 special celebrations and 3% by people for sacrifice. 
 Traders are an important category of market agents 
 who are more experienced and skilled than any other 
 type of buyer or seller in testing the product 
 quality attributes of each animal. They are also 
 skilled in testing the true value of an animal and 
 the value a particular type of buyer or seller may put 
 on the animal. These knowledge and skill mostly 
 influence the margin they can come from 
 each transaction. 
 Some traders in the sample markets bought local 
 animals from the farm gate or at the market for 
 resale in the market while other traders brought 
 northern animals from terminal city-based  markets in 
 Oyo and Ibadan. Some local traders maintained stalls 
 at the market where few animals were kept on 
 non-market days to meet the emergency needs of 
 local buyers. Transactions during non-market days 
 were not watched/supervised in this study. During a market 
 day, a buyer or a seller, especially a trader, could 
 be involved in multiple transactions-buying/selling 
 a few animals or buying and reselling the same 
 animal the same day. It was hard to keep track of 
 such many transactions. Since records of all individual transactions were kept, a trader involved in 
 
