 There are a big differences between species 
 and breeds (bought something for money) for different purposes (Table 
 1). The sample markets being (away from cities) with supply 
 country for WAD sheep and goats, traders would 
 be (usually/ in a common and regular way) expected to sell but not (instance of buying something for money) 
 Y' ankasa sheep and Red Sokoto goats of the north, 
 and this was in fact the case. Ninety percent of the 
 Y' ankasa sheep were (bought something for money) by people for 
 the Christmas and Eid-el-Kabir special celebrations for which 
 Red Sokoto goat was also preferred to WAD sheep 
 and goats. WAD goat was the favourite animal for 
 sacrifice, butchering and catering but Red Sokoto 
 goat was the most important animal used for (formal, special events or series of actions) such as funerals, births and marriages. 
 A large number of animals are traded around the 
 times of special celebrations. Supplies and sales of animals 
 peaked in June-July happening with the Muslim 
 special celebration of Eid-el-Kabir. A smaller peak in December 
 (happened at the same time with the Christmas-New Year special celebrations. 
 Supplies built up over the few weeks before Eidel-Kabir in July. Actual supplies in June-July 1990 
 accounted for 55% of total supply for the year with 
 July alone accounting for 43% of the total supply for 
 the year. Out of the total July supply, 73% were on 
 offer on three market days within 10 days before 
 Eid-el-Kabir. During the whole 14 months period 
 
 25 
 
 M.A. Jabbar /Agricultural Money flow 18 ( 1997) 21-30 
 
 supply per market per day averaged 74 animals but 
 supply averaged 117 and 47 animals (match up each pair of items in order) 
 during peak special celebration periods (June-July, DecemberJanuary) and other (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) months. Northern animals 
 made up/was equal to 40-50% of daily supplies during the 
 peak special celebration periods and 20-28% of the daily supplies during other months. This points to/shows that northern suppliers mostly target special celebration related markets 
 in the south. 
 Watched/followed age and live weight of the traded animals are shown in Table 2. Overall, Y' ankasa sheep 
 were the oldest and heaviest animals while WAD 
 goats were the lightest. Females were older and 
 heavier than males. Among different end uses, animals bought for rearing and sacrifice were younger 
 and lighter than those bought for trading, (formal, special events or series of actions), special celebrations and butchering/catering. Buying 
 younger and lighter animals for rearing would be 
 expected but buying younger and lighter animals for 
 
 sacrifice points to/shows that when happiness-causing god in the 
 spirit of sacrifice, size of the animal is maybe not 
 important. Animals traded during June-July were of 
 higher average weight than those traded during other 
 months. This was mostly because heavier northern 
 animals were traded in June-July for the Muslim 
 special celebration of Eid-el-Kabir. It may be noted that Eid-elKabir happens 10-11 days sooner every year due to 
 the Moon-related cycle, but whenever it happens, larger animals would be (usually/ in a common and regular way) (bought something for money). 
