 the coefficient of age square of this group is not 
 significant. The sign of weight square is positive in 
 the overall model and for rearing, butchering and 
 special celebration, pointing to/showing that price increases at an increasing rate as animals get heavier, though this relationship is significant only in the case of special celebration, pointing to/showing higher higher cost is paid for heavier animals 
 murdered for special celebration. For trading, (formal, special events or series of actions) and 
 sacrifice, the negative sign of weight square points to/shows 
 that less higher cost is paid for heavier animals, especially those (bought) for trading and (formal, special events or series of actions). 
 Other things being equal, the results also show the 
 following. 
 (a) In the overall model, traders, butchers/ caterers 
 and people buying for (formal, special events or series of actions) paid much lower prices and those buying for special celebrations paid higher prices than prices paid by farmers 
 for rearing, which was used as the base category. 
 Traders and butchers I caterers paid (a) little lower 
 prices than that paid by people buying for 
 (formal, special events or series of actions). There was no a big difference between prices paid for animals (bought something for money) for rearing 
 and for sacrifice. 
 (b) In the overall model, WAD sheep and 
 Y' ankasa sheep prices were much higher and 
 Red Sokoto goat prices were much lower than 
 WAD goats. Prices of Y'ankasa sheep were much higher than those for WAD sheep. But the 
 pattern varied between purpose clearly stated/particular models. All 
 types of buyers paid much higher prices for 
 WAD sheep compared to WAD goats, except in the 
 case of butchers/caterers. There was no significant 
 difference between WAD goat and Red Sokoto goat 
 prices for animals (bought something for money) for rearing, trading and 
 special celebration but Red Sokoto goat prices were much lower in case of (instances of buying things for money) for (formal, special events or series of actions) and 
 butchering/ catering. Y' ankasa sheep prices were 
 much higher than those for WAD sheep in the 
 overall model as well as in the model for special celebration, for 
 which most Y' ankasa sheep were (bought). 
 (c) In the overall model, prices for females were 
 lower than for males, but the differences were not 
 significant. However, the pattern varied between purpose clearly stated/particular models. Females (bought something for money) for rearing, 
 trading and sacrifice were paid higher prices but 
 significant only in the case of rearing which is 
 agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the breeding goals of the buyers. 
 Females (bought something for money) for butchering/ catering, cere- 
 
 monies and special celebrations were paid lower prices. The 
 difference was significant only in the case of (instances of buying things for money) for special celebration, because hopefully a male is 
 murdered for Eid-el-Kabir. 
 (d) In the overall model, prices in Apomu market 
 were much lower than in Oja. However, in 
 purpose clearly stated/particular models, prices in Apomu were 
 higher sometimes and lower in others but in no 
 case the difference was significant. 
 (e) The month of (instance of buying something for money) was grouped into 
 a few groups on the basis of test runs which showed 
 that prices were almost the same  during certain periods. In the 
 overall model, compared to December 1989-January 
 1990 period (which was carefully thought about/believed as the base), 
 February to May 1990 prices were significantly 
 lower, and August to November 1990 prices were 
 also much lower. June-July and December 
 1990-January 1991 prices were not significantly 
 different from the base period. In the purpose clearly stated/particular models, the signs, high levels and importance 
 of occasional price differences were highly variable 
 though the general pattern was the same as that for 
 the overall model except in the case of special celebration 
 (instances of buying things for money), which was time specific. In the case of 
 special celebration, April-May prices were much lower 
 than the previous December-January prices but 
 June-July prices were much higher. The reason is that the special celebration held in June-July period was 
 more important than that held in April-May. The 
 prices in next December-January were significantly 
 lower compared to previous December-January, the 
 base period. 
 
 4. Discussion and end/end result 
 In the southwest Nigerian (away from cities) markets supplies, 
 sales and prices of small (buffaloes, deer, antelopes, etc.) peak before the 
 Muslim special celebration of Eid-el-Kabir and a little bit 
 during the Christmas-New Year period. Throughout 
 the year, animals are (bought) for rearing, trading, 
 butchering/ catering, sacrifice and different (formal, special events or series of actions) such as marriage, funeral, birthdays, and for 
 special celebrations. There are strong preferences among buyers 
 for clearly stated/particular species and breeds of small (buffaloes, deer, antelopes, etc.) 
 for clearly stated/particular purposes as pointed to/showed by a big differences in the amount/quantity of (instances of buying things for money). Local WAD 
 goats and sheep are preferred for rearing because of 
 
 M.A. Jabbar /Agricultural Money flow 18 (1997) 21-30 
 
 their helpful change to the local (surrounding conditions), for 
 butchering/catering because of the local people' 
 taste and preference for the meat of local animals, 
 and for sacrifice which has long cultural tradition 
 attached to local animals. Local species /breeds were 
 also preferred for murdering on the occasion of 
 different (formal, special events or series of actions) when entertaining guests was the 
 first (or most important) goal, and for special celebrations. But the present 
 purchase pattern points to/shows that this preference pattern 
 is changing with more and more more northern 
 species/breeds used for these purposes. Northern 
 animals made up/was equal to 34% of supplies in the present 
 survey compared to 28% reported for a almost the same  survey managed and did/done during 1983-85 in which the same 
 markets were included (Francis, 1990). 
 Average supplies per market day including peak 
 period was 35 in 1983-1985 compared to 74 in the 
 1989-1991 survey. The (your share of sales out of all sales) of southern 
 animals in total supply and sales have remained 
 stable between the two survey periods. However, the 
 number of northern animals in the southern markets 
 in the (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) as well as peak market periods have 
 increased significantly over time. 
 One of the main reason for increased penetration of northern animals into the southern (away from cities) markets is that transportation of animals from the north 
 has become faster, easier and cheaper due to better 
 and wider roads that allow larger lorries to carry 
 many more animals per trip. Within the southern part 
 of the country, connection of (away from cities) markets to city-based 
 centers, such as lbadan with Apomu, has improved. 
 As a result, northern animals can be sold at more 
 competitive prices at (away from cities) markets. 
 (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) prices of WAD goats are either much higher or almost the same as  Red Sokoto goat prices 
 depending on the purpose for buying but (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) 
 prices of WAD sheep are much higher than 
 either goat breed for almost all purposes, pointing to/showing a 
 strong buyer preference for this breed. 
 (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) prices of Y' ankasa sheep, (bought something for money) 
 mostly for the Muslim special celebration of Eid-el-Kabir, is 
 higher than WAD sheep prices. However, the overall 
 (your share of sales out of all sales) of WAD sheep is only 9% compared to 
 70% for WAD goats and 21% for Red Sokoto goats. 
 It is probable that under strong price competition 
 from northern goats, and increasing personal acceptance of northern animals for purposes for which 
 (before that/before now) local species/breeds were preferred, the 
 
 29 
 
 (your share of sales out of all sales) of WAD sheep may (lower in number/get worse) further. On 
 the other hand, lower (your share of sales out of all sales) and significantly 
 higher (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) prices for WAD sheep paid by all 
 categories of buyers point to/show that there is excess 
 demand for this breed and so both producers and 
 people should benefit from increased WAD sheep 
 production. Producers and sellers will benefit by 
 targeting clearly stated/particular buyer categories and times of the 
 year because of strong buyer preferences for specific 
 species /breeds of animals for clearly stated/particular purposes and 
 because of their desire to pay different prices 
 agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with their preferences. Increasing market 
 share of northern animals in (away from cities) markets is (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that northern producers and traders are taking 
 advantage of these (groups of customers/chances to sell products). 
 
